Part 1: Data

Generalizability In the beginning,The data set is comprised of 651 randomly sampled movies produced and released before 2016.Every single movie has the equal chance to be selected to ensure represent all the movies in the United States.We can conclude random sampling was used in this process.The method is valid but not sampling methods. But since all movies used to represent the cross-section country, I think movies_data now can generalized to the U.S. movies. Causality Because the data is observational, not experimental, and no random assigment was assigned to the sample, we can therefore only find correlation. Causality cannot be found.

# There are some NAs. These will be removed.
# create dataframe with data of interest for analysis
movies_int <- movies %>%
mutate( feature_film    =  ifelse( title_type  == "Feature Film", "yes", "no" ) , 
          drama         =  ifelse( genre       == "Drama",        "yes", "no" ) ,
          mpaa_rating_R =  ifelse( mpaa_rating == "R",            "yes", "no" ) , 
          oscar_season  =  ifelse( 10<=thtr_rel_month & thtr_rel_month<=12, "yes", "no" ) ,
          summer_season =  ifelse(  5<=thtr_rel_month & thtr_rel_month<=8,  "yes", "no" )  ) %>%
select( feature_film, drama,         runtime,        mpaa_rating_R,    thtr_rel_year, 
          oscar_season, summer_season, imdb_rating,    imdb_num_votes,   critics_score, 
          best_pic_nom, best_pic_win,  best_actor_win, best_actress_win, best_dir_win, 
          top200_box,   
          audience_score 
          )
# remove observations  NAs
movies_int <- na.omit(movies_int)

Part 4: Modeling

# Exclude observations with missing values in the data set
ggpairs(data = movies_int, 
        columns = c("thtr_rel_year","runtime","imdb_rating","critics_score","imdb_num_votes","audience_score"),progress = FALSE)

#Bayesian Model Averaging considers all possible models using the pre-selected predictors, allowing selection of a model with consideration of uncertainty. The determination and analysis for BMA, with this amount of models and data, is not too long. Thereofore, BMA will be performed, as opposed to elimination of variables via a criterion like BIC 
bma_score <- bas.lm( audience_score ~ . - critics_score - audience_score, data = movies_int,
                   prior = "ZS-null",          
                   modelprior = uniform())
summary(bma_score)

#There is a plot of the residuals vs. fitted (predicted) values
m_bma_score_aug <- movies_int %>%
  dplyr::select(audience_score) %>%
  mutate(fitted = BMA_pred_audience_score$fit,
         resid  = audience_score - fitted,
         std_resid = resid/sd(resid) )       # standardised residuals
#This is the plot.

Part 5: Prediction

There is a Chinese movie called “Crouching tigger , Hidden Dragon”

# Create a new data frame.
# We can find this information from the internet.
movies_a <- movies_int
movies_a$feature_film[600] <- "no"
movies_a$drama[600] <- "yes"
movies_a$runtime[600] <- 120
movies_a$mpaa_rating_R[600] <- "no"
movies_a$oscar_season[600] <- "yes"
movies_a$summer_season[600] <- "no"
movies_a$imdb_rating[600] <- 6.0
movies_a$thtr_rel_year[600] <- 2001
movies_a$best_pic_nom[600] <- "yes"
movies_a$best_pic_win[600] <- "yes"
movies_a$best_actor_win[600] <- "no"
movies_a$best_actress_win[600] <- "no"
movies_a$best_dir_win[600] <- "no"
movies_a$top200_box[600] <- "no"
movies_a$critics_score[600] <- 87
movies_a$audience_score[600] <- 90
movies_a <- movies_a[600,]
# prediction using BMA model and new data
BMA_new_pred_audience_score <- predict(object = bma_score, newdata = movies_a, 
                                       se.fit = TRUE, estimator = "BMA")
confint(BMA_new_pred_audience_score)
##          2.5%   97.5%     pred
## [1,] 35.50908 75.7795 54.93863
## attr(,"Probability")
## [1] 0.95
## attr(,"class")
## [1] "confint.bas"

Obviously, our model is not very good.The Credible Interval around this prediction provides a measure of uncertainty for the prediction. The interpretation is: “there is a probability of 95% that the audience score lies between 35.5% and 76.8%”.

The predicted score is 55%.

But actually the movie socre is 86 % https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/crouching_tiger_hidden_dragon

Part 6: Conclusion

The data used for modelling included characteristics that are not ideal for the modelling within scope of this course. For example:there were categorical variables with low counts of one of their levels there were outliers signs of association among the categorical explanatory variables deviation from normal distributions, including cases of extreme skew and flat middle of the range non-linearilty in the relationships between most predictors and the reponse variable non-constant variance in the residuals.
